\begin_inset Formula $p'D_{w}x(p,w)=1$
\end_inset

, (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $p'D_{p}x(p,w)=-x(p,w)'$
\end_inset

, (iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $p'S(p,w)=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous fact part (i) implies that there exists at least one normal
 good, the reason is that there has to be at least one 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\partial_{w}x_{l}(p,w)>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{l}p_{l}'\partial_{w}x_{l}(p,w)=1$
\end_inset

.
 In general, you can see that the Walras' law also restricts the behavior
 of the wealth effects.
 The previous fact part (iii) are restrictions on the behavior of the consumptio
n changes to Slutsky compensated price changes.
 
\end_layout

