\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to study three very important sets in consumer theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Upper contour set) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a rational preference on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The upper contour set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $B^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in X|y\succeq x\}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This set captures the better than equal alternatives of any given commodity
 under the rational preferences.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Lower contour set) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 be a rational preference on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 The lower contour set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in X$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\succeq}(x)=\{y\in X|x\succeq y\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And finally the well-known set (indifference curve/set).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
(Indifference set) Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\succeq$
\end_inset

