\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
firm 
\series default
represents the production possibilities of household, individuals, corporations
 or other businesses.
 The firm may represent actual production or potential of production.
 The theory of the firm is concerned with the question of: What can a firm
 do? The firm for us, is a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

black box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that is able to transform inputs into outputs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Production Sets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We fix 
\begin_inset Formula $L\geq1$
\end_inset

 commodities, a 
\series bold
production vector or plan
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $y=(y_{1},\cdots,y_{L})\in\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

 describes the (net) outputs of the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 commodities.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{l}\geq0$
\end_inset

 denotes output and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{l}<0$
\end_inset

 denotes input.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of all production plans that are technologically feasible is called
 the 
\series bold
production set, 
\begin_inset Formula $Y\subset\mathbb{R}^{L}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in Y$
\end_inset

 is feasible, any 
\begin_inset Formula $y\notin Y$
\end_inset

 is not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production set is the data or the primitive of the theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes it is useful to describe the production set, using a function
 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 called the 
\series bold
transformation function.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is 
\begin_inset Formula $Y=\{y\in\mathbb{R}^{L}:F(y)\leq0\}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F(y)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is an element of the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of 
\begin_inset Formula $\{y\in\mathbb{R}^{L}|F(y)=0\}$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\series bold
transformation frontier.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The Marginal Rate of Transformation MRT of any two goods 
\begin_inset Formula $l,k$
\end_inset

 is the ratio:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRT_{lk}(\overline{y})=\frac{\partial F(y)/\partial y_{l}}{\partial F(y)/\partial y_{k}},\quad F(\overline{y})=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The MRT measures how much the net output of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 can increase if the firm decreases the net output of 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 by one marginal unit.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Technologies with Different Inputs and Outputs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We let 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 denote the number of outputs and 
\begin_inset Formula $L-M$
\end_inset

 the number of inputs, usually the vector of outputs is denotes as 
\begin_inset Formula $q=(q_{1},\cdots,q_{M})\geq0$
\end_inset

 and the vector of used inputs is 
\begin_inset Formula $z=(z_{1},\cdots,z_{L-M})\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Here, we eliminate the negative sign for inputs as they stand separate
 from outputs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A particular case of interest is when 
\begin_inset Formula $M=1$
\end_inset

, in that case we can write the production set using a 
\series bold
production function, 
\series default
that gives the maximum amount of output one can reach with a level of input
 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q\leq f(z)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The production set is then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Y=\{(-z',q)'\in\mathbb{R}^{L}|q-f(z)\leq0\quad z\geq0,z\in\mathbb{R}^{L-1}\}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Marginal rate of technical substitution -MRTS-.
 The MRTS of goods 
\begin_inset Formula $l,k$
\end_inset

 is the ratio:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MRTS_{lk}(\overline{z})=\frac{\partial f(\overline{z})/\partial z_{l}}{\partial f(\overline{z})/\partial z_{k}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a fixed level 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{q}=f(\overline{z})$
\end_inset

, the MRTS of 
\begin_inset Formula $l,k$
\end_inset

 measures by how much the input of 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 must be increased for a reduction of a marginal unit of 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 to keep the production at the maximum level 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{q}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is analogous to the Marginal Rate of Substitution in consumer theory,
 where we asked by how much the demand of one good changed with respect
 to other to keep the utility constant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
